The Eph receptors are the largest family of receptor tyrosine kinases and include at least 14 structurally related members. Initially isolated as orphan receptors (lacking known ligands), at least eight Eph ligands—ephrins—have recently been reported (Fig. 4
) [95], [96]. Recent advances have started to elucidate the developmental functions and biochemistry of Eph receptor tyrosine kinases and their membrane-bound ligands, ephrins. Unlike most ligands, ephrins do not function in a soluble form but must be membrane-bound to activate their receptor(s) [95] (Fig. 5
).
